				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{P}}_{{\mathrm{ICO}}_2}$$\end{document}PICO2) to ensure safe levels for existing and future spacesuits9. Another relevant technology being developed is the pilot mask sensor (MASES) system, which provides on-board, real-time monitoring of pilot breathing gas. The mask has an embedded probe with luminescence sensors to measure relative humidity, pressure, temperature, pCO2, and pO2. Real-time monitoring of pCO2 and pO2 allows closed-loop control of the on-board O2 generation system and is based upon the pilot’s respiration10. Although the mask was developed for military aviators, the system has application to EVA. As spacesuit design continues, the inclusion of systems capable of monitoring the inlet and outlet gases, while providing data on metabolic expenditures, can increase planetary EVA safety.
